We can write the update rule for $\mathbf{h}\_j$ as follows:

hj=f(zj)=f(Wxj+Uhj−1)\mathbf{h}\_j = f(\mathbf{z}\_j) = f(\mathbf{W} \mathbf{x}\_j + \mathbf{U} \mathbf{h}\_{j-1})hj​=f(zj​)=f(Wxj​+Uhj−1​)

We want to compute the partial derivative of $\mathbf{h}\_m$ with respect to $\mathbf{h}\_1$, which we can write using the chain rule as follows:

\begin{align\*}
\frac{\partial \mathbf{h}*m}{\partial \mathbf{h}*1} &= \frac{\partial \mathbf{h}*m}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{m-1}} \frac{\partial \mathbf{h}*{m-1}}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{m-2}} \cdots \frac{\partial \mathbf{h}*{2}}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{1}} \
&= \prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} \frac{\partial \mathbf{h}*{j+1}}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{j}} \
&= \prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} \frac{\partial f(\mathbf{z}*{j+1})}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{j}} \
&= \prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} \frac{\partial f(\mathbf{z}*{j+1})}{\partial \mathbf{z}*{j+1}} \frac{\partial \mathbf{z}*{j+1}}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{j}}
\end{align\*}

To compute the first term in the last line, we use the chain rule again:

∂f(zj+1)∂zj+1=f′(zj+1)\frac{\partial f(\mathbf{z}\_{j+1})}{\partial \mathbf{z}\_{j+1}} = f'(\mathbf{z}\_{j+1})∂zj+1​∂f(zj+1​)​=f′(zj+1​)

For the second term, we have:

\begin{align\*}
\frac{\partial \mathbf{z}*{j+1}}{\partial \mathbf{h}*{j}} &= \frac{\partial (\mathbf{W} \mathbf{x}*{j+1} + \mathbf{U} \mathbf{h}*{j})}{\partial \mathbf{h}\_{j}} \
&= \mathbf{U}
\end{align\*}

Putting it all together, we have:

∂hm∂h1=∏j=1m−1f′(zj+1)U\frac{\partial \mathbf{h}\_m}{\partial \mathbf{h}\_1} = \prod\_{j=1}^{m-1} f'(\mathbf{z}\_{j+1}) \mathbf{U}∂h1​∂hm​​=∏j=1m−1​f′(zj+1​)U

This is the explicit expression for the Jacobian $\partial \mathbf{h}\_m / \partial \mathbf{h}\_1$ in terms of $\mathbf{U}$, the $\mathbf{z}\_j$'s, and $f'$.

